"Jochem P.","Impacts of a carbon dioxide emissions trading scheme in German road transportation: Mesoeconomic analysis",2009,"Transportation Research Record",,"2139",,"153","160",,,10.3141/2139-18,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76149096825&partnerID=40&md5=b34f556c4152bcdc3ed5e1ecedca41a5","Institute for Economic Policy Research (IWW), Universität Karlsruhe TH, P.O. Box 6980, Karlsruhe D-76128, Germany","Jochem, P., Institute for Economic Policy Research (IWW), Universität Karlsruhe TH, P.O. Box 6980, Karlsruhe D-76128, Germany","To attempt to counter the possible impacts of global warming, the European Union decided to ratify the Kyoto Protocol and promised to reduce its carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions by 8%, compared with 1990 levels, by 2010. One of the policies that has been implemented to achieve this is the European Emission Trading Scheme (ETS) for CO2 certificates. So far, the transportation sector, which contributes about 28% of European CO2 emissions, has been exempt from ETS, although a further increase in CO 2 emissions from the transportation sector is expected in the coming years. Furthermore, this is the only sector in which emissions have increased (by about 32% since 1990). The inclusion of road transportation in ETS is feasible after 2012. A partial mesoeconomic model was used to assess the impacts of a CO2 emissions trading scheme in German road transportation. A hypothetical CO2 emissions trading scheme with an open alternative and a closed alternative was applied to the simulated German road transportation sector. The effects on certificate prices and fuel demand as a result of the individual reactions of households and freight forwarders were calculated. It became apparent that from the current perspective the willingness of households to pay for prestigious (but fuel-inefficient) cars is outweighed by technical mitigation costs in other sectors. Thus, in an open trading scheme without major changes in transportation demand, the main effect will be steady CO2 emissions in road transportation but large payments to other sectors for mitigation.",,"A-carbon; Emission trading scheme; Emissions Trading Scheme; European Union; Freight forwarders; Fuel demand; KYOTO protocol; Main effect; Mitigation costs; Road transportation; Transportation demand; Transportation sector; Air quality; Carbon dioxide; Commerce; Emission control; Global warming; International law; Roads and streets; Motor transportation",,,,,,"Climate change 2007: The physical science basis, summary for policymakers (2007) Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Geneva; Ziesing, H.-J., Trotz klimaschutzabkommen: Weltweit steigende CO2-Emissionen (2007) DIW Wochenbericht, 35, pp. 486-498; (2007) CO2-Minderung im Verkehr, , Final Report. Federal Environmental Agency of Germany, Berlin; (2000) Nature Conservation, and Nuclear Safety of Germany, , Nationales Klimaschutzprogramm. Federal Ministry for the Environment, Berlin; Nachhaltige Energieversorgung unter den Bedingungen der Globalisierung und der Liberalisierung (2002) Report 14/9400, , Final Report; Nationaler Allokationsplan 2008-2012 für die Bundesrepublik Deutschland (2006) Nature Conservation, and Nuclear Safety of Germany, , Federal Ministry for the Environment, Berlin; Schafer, A., Carbon dioxide emissions from world passenger transport: Reduction options (2000) Transportation Research Record: Journal of the Transportation Research Board, 1738, pp. 20-29. , TRB, National Research Council, Washington, D.C; Decicco, J., Ross, M., Recent advances in automotive technology and the cost-effectiveness of fuel economy improvement (1996) Transportation Research, 1 (2 PART D), pp. 79-96; (2006) Cost Effectiveness of CO2 Mitigation in Transport, , Final Report. CE Delft, Delft, Netherlands; (2007) Kosten und Potenziale der Vermeidung von Treibhsuagasen in Deutschland, , Federation of German Industries, Berlin; Goodwin, P., Dargay, J., Hanly, M., Elasticities of road traffic a